---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import CompareBody from '../components/CompareBody.astro';
---
<Layout seoSlug="/slicewp-vs-asteris">
  <CompareBody
    rivalName="SliceWP"
    rivalTagline="A lightweight WordPress affiliate plugin with a free core and Pro upgrade. Modern UI, focused on single-tier programs."
    rivalUrl="https://slicewp.com"
    intro="SliceWP Pro is a lightweight, well-designed WordPress affiliate plugin that suits stores running single-tier programs and a small affiliate list. Asteris Affiliates extends the same self-hosted model with two-tier (MLM) referrals, AI swipe-copy, Stripe Connect direct payouts, EDD + Surecart adapters and cloud-assist fraud detection — included from $149/yr Starter (Asteris) vs SliceWP Pro at $299/yr base."
    whenRivalWins={[
      'You want the simplest possible UI for a single-tier program and you do not need MLM',
      'You value SliceWP\'s polish and design simplicity above feature breadth',
      'You\'re on WooCommerce only and you don\'t need an EDD or Surecart adapter',
    ]}
    whenAsterisWins={[
      'Two-tier (MLM) referrals — SliceWP does not offer this at any tier or via any add-on',
      'AI swipe-copy generator — no SliceWP equivalent',
      'Cloud-assist fraud detection (opt-in, SHA-256 hashed) — no SliceWP equivalent',
      'Stripe Connect Express direct payouts at 0.25% — no SliceWP equivalent',
      'PayPal API auto-batch — SliceWP has manual payouts only',
      'EDD adapter + Surecart adapter in core',
      'Vanity /go/ landing pages with cookie + view tracking',
      'A/B email testing on transactional emails',
      'Real-time stats REST API (cursor-paginated, transient-cached)',
      'Asteris Starter is $149/yr vs SliceWP Pro at $299/yr base',
    ]}
    comparisonRows={[
      { feature: 'Base price (1 site)',           rival: '$299/yr',               asteris: '$149/yr',                  win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Free core tier',                 rival: 'Yes',                  asteris: 'Yes (25 affiliates)',      win: 'tie' },
      { feature: 'Two-tier (MLM) referrals',       rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included from Starter',    win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'AI swipe-copy generator',        rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Cloud-assist fraud detection',   rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Opt-in (hashed)',          win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Stripe Connect direct payouts',  rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'PayPal API auto-batch',          rival: 'Manual only',          asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'EDD adapter',                    rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Surecart adapter',               rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Vanity /go/ landing pages',      rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'A/B email testing',              rival: 'Not available',        asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'WP-CLI commands',                rival: 'Limited',              asteris: 'Full suite',               win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Per-product commission rates',   rival: 'Add-on',               asteris: 'Included',                 win: 'asteris' },
      { feature: 'Self-hosted',                    rival: 'Yes',                  asteris: 'Yes',                      win: 'tie' },
      { feature: 'GPL-licensed code',              rival: 'Yes',                  asteris: 'Yes (GPL-2.0+)',           win: 'tie' },
    ]}
    migrateSlug="/migrate/from-slicewp"
  >
    <section class="prose">
      <div class="prose-inner">
        <h2>What SliceWP gets right — and what it leaves on the table</h2>
        <p>SliceWP is genuinely good at what it does. The free core is more capable than most "free" plugins in the WordPress affiliate category, the admin UI is one of the cleanest in the space, and the team ships steadily. If you're shopping for a SliceWP alternative because you want a "better SliceWP" you'll be disappointed — Asteris is a different shape of product, with a much bigger feature surface. The stores moving across to us are the ones who hit a feature wall SliceWP doesn't intend to close.</p>
        <h3>The MLM wall</h3>
        <p>Two-tier referrals (where affiliates earn a small commission on sub-affiliates they recruit) isn't on the SliceWP roadmap that we can find. If your program ever wants to add a tier-2 layer — and most growing programs do, because compounding referrals are the single biggest growth lever in affiliate marketing — SliceWP isn't going to get there. Asteris ships MLM in Starter. <a href="/docs/commissions/two-tier">How two-tier works →</a></p>
        <h3>The cart wall</h3>
        <p>SliceWP is WooCommerce-only. If you ever want to run an affiliate program on Easy Digital Downloads or Surecart in addition to (or instead of) WC, SliceWP can't track those carts. Asteris ships EDD and Surecart adapters in core. <a href="/features">All cart integrations →</a></p>
        <h3>The payout wall</h3>
        <p>SliceWP supports manual payouts (mark as paid, send the money yourself). Asteris ships Stripe Connect Express direct payouts at 0.25%, PayPal Payouts API at 2% with batch scheduling, and bank-CSV export in AU + US formats. If you're running more than ~30 affiliates, the manual-payout overhead becomes painful fast.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose dark">
      <div class="prose-inner">
        <h2>The price comparison, in context</h2>
        <p>SliceWP's free core covers small programs well. SliceWP Pro adds the features most growing programs need (verified on their pricing page before purchase). Asteris Affiliates Starter is $149/yr for one site, includes every Pro-equivalent feature SliceWP offers, plus the MLM, AI swipe, Surecart, EDD, Stripe Connect, cloud-fraud and A/B email features SliceWP doesn't offer at any price.</p>
        <p>On 3 sites: SliceWP Pro 3-site is one price point; Asteris Pro is $299/yr (3 sites). On 10 sites: Asteris Agency is $549/yr. The Asteris cohort pricing locks for the life of an active subscription. <a href="/pricing">Pricing comparison →</a></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose">
      <div class="prose-inner">
        <h2>Migrating from SliceWP to Asteris</h2>
        <p>SliceWP exports affiliates and referrals via the standard WP admin export. Our <a href="/migrate/from-slicewp">SliceWP migration guide</a> covers the WP-CLI command that reads that export and recreates affiliates with their balances, referrals with their attribution, and historical visits where SliceWP recorded them. The legacy referral parameter <code>?affwp=...</code> (or SliceWP's equivalent) keeps working via a compatibility redirect, so existing affiliate links in the wild don't break.</p>
        <p>Most SliceWP-to-Asteris migrations finish in under 30 minutes. Pro and Agency licences get migration assistance included — email <a href="mailto:support@asterisaffiliates.com">support@asterisaffiliates.com</a> with your licence key if you'd like us to run it for you.</p>

        <h2>The free-tier comparison most stores skip</h2>
        <p>SliceWP and Asteris both ship a free tier — that's worth flagging because most paid affiliate plugins don't. The free tiers solve different problems, though, and the right zero-cost answer depends on which constraints bite first.</p>
        <p>SliceWP's free core has no hard cap on affiliate count. It supports WooCommerce, has the core admin UI, and is genuinely usable for a small program. The constraint kicks in at the feature ceiling — no MLM, limited reporting, manual payouts only, no AI swipe, no fraud detection layer beyond basic IP throttling. You hit the wall when you want a Pro feature, not when you hit a count threshold.</p>
        <p>Asteris Free hits the opposite constraint pattern: feature set is identical to paid except for four gated Pro features (MLM, AI swipe-copy, cloud-assist fraud, Stripe Connect direct payouts), but there's a hard cap at 25 active affiliates. You hit the wall when you outgrow the cap, regardless of which features you've enabled. Most stores hit the count cap before they need a Pro feature — and at that point, $149/yr Starter unlocks unlimited affiliates plus all four Pro features at once.</p>
        <p>The practical implication: if you expect to stay under 25 affiliates indefinitely, SliceWP free might serve longer because it doesn't cap count. If you're a growing program planning to hit 50+ affiliates within a year, Asteris Free + planned upgrade to Starter is the cheaper total path because you skip the SliceWP Pro middle step. <a href="/free">See the Asteris Free tier →</a></p>

        <h2>When SliceWP is still the right answer</h2>
        <p>If you're running a tiny single-tier program (under 20 affiliates), only on WooCommerce, and never plan to add MLM or non-WC carts, SliceWP's free core is genuinely a good answer and you don't need to pay anyone. We'll also say what we said for AffiliateWP: if you're invested in SliceWP and happy with it, stay. The migration cost isn't immediate value — the value resets the moment you need a feature Asteris ships and SliceWP doesn't.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </CompareBody>
</Layout>

<style>
  .prose { padding: 64px 24px; background: #fff; border-top: 1px solid var(--c-border); }
  .prose.dark { background: var(--c-bg); }
  .prose-inner { max-width: 820px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .prose h2 { font-size: clamp(24px, 3vw, 32px); margin: 36px 0 18px; }
  .prose h2:first-child { margin-top: 0; }
  .prose h3 { font-size: 18px; margin: 24px 0 10px; color: var(--c-mint); }
  .prose p { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.65; color: var(--c-text); margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .prose a { color: var(--c-mint); font-weight: 600; }
  .prose code { background: rgba(0,0,0,0.06); padding: 1px 5px; border-radius: 3px; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 13px; }
  .prose strong { color: var(--c-text); font-weight: 700; }
</style>
